Geoderma, 33 (1984) 119--134  Elsevier Science Publishers B.V., Amsterdam --Printed in The Netherlands    119    EVALUATION OF PHOSPHORUS SORPTION BY AN ALLOPHANIC SOIL    JAIME II~IGUEZ and ROSA Ma VAL  Departamento de Edafologfa, Facultad de Ciencias, Universidad de Navarra, Pamplona  (Spain)  (Received January 15, 1982; revised version accepted December 15, 1983)    ABSTRACT    Ifiiguez, J. and Val, R.M., 1984. Evaluation of phosphorus sorption by an allophanic soil.  Geoderma, 33: 119--134.    Solutions containing different P concentrations were equilibrated with samples of an  allophanic soil from Navarra (Spain) to determine whether P sorption conformed qualita-  tively and quantitatively to the Langmuir, Freundlich and Sokolowska isotherms.  Phosphorus sorption conformed to the Langmuir isotherm. When the sorption data  were plotted according to the conventional and Hofstee forms, two linear relationships  were obtained. At the lower equilibrium P concentrations the K1 parameter determined  by regression analysis was higher than those corresponding to higher equilibrium P con-  centrations. The values obtained for K~ and K2 by the conventional and Hofstee equa-  tions were different. A procedure for evaluating the coefficients for higher equilibrium P  concentrations was proposed. The K1 and K2 values so obtained allowed us to generate  an experimental curve by addition of calculated adsorption data. This suggests that the  curve-splitting technique is satisfactory.  The sorption data also conformed to the Freundlich and Sokolowska equations, but in  the latter it was necessary to evaluate two different sets of parameters.  The same experimental data can be adjusted to the three different equations, in one  case with only one set of constants and in the other two cases with two different sets of  parameters, one for the lower P concentrations and the other for the higher ones. Besides,  to fit the experimental data to the Langmuir and Sokolowska equations, it was necessary  to split the isotherm into two regions and these two regions were different for  the Langmuir and the Sokolowska equations. This suggests that the parameters do not  have any chemical signification and that they are only "curve fitting".  A study of the effect of pH on the P sorption indicated that low pH notably increased  the P sorption.  The soil samples had very high phosphate sorption capacity probably due to the very  large specific surface and reactivity of the allophane.    INTRODUCTION    Andosols are widely distributed in the world and possess many special  properties such as low bulk density, high water holding capacity, high humus  content and large phosphate adsorption capacity. Their clay fractions mainly    0016-7061/84/$03.00  1984 Elsevier Science Publishers B.V.    120    consist of allophane, with the chemical formula m SiO:, A1203, /l H20,  where m = 1--2, but considerable variation in chemical composition has been  reported (Yoshinaga et al., 1968; Wada, 1978). Yoshinaga et al. (1968)  reported the existence of small but significant amounts of Fe.  Allophane adsorbs cations and anions from neutral salt solutions. Many  attempts have been made to clarify the reaction mechanisms of soil com-  ponents with anions, especially phosphate, because of its practical impor-  tance in agriculture.  Interactions of anions with allophane involve three different reactions:  non-specific adsorption, specific adsorption and decomposition of the al-  lophane induced specifically by adsorbed anions. The non-specific adsorp-  tion refers to adsorption of anions by simple coulombic interaction with  positive charges on A1--OH~ or Fe--OH~ groups. The specific adsorption  refers to incorporation of the anion as a ligand in the coordination shell of  an A1 or Fe atom (Wada, 1978). (These reactions have been extensively  studied for hydrous Fe oxides.) The induced decomposition of the al-  lophane signifies the precipitation of A1 or Fe compounds.  The results obtained by Imai et al. (1981) about the kinetics of adsorption  and its associated calorimetry, suggest that in allophanic soils very high in  organic matter, the organo-mineral complex seems to form a rather open  microstructure such that phosphate ions at low P additions are adsorbed on  relatively low energy surfaces only. When larger amounts of P are added,  more P-reactive surfaces are exposed; the loosely bound organic matter is  progressively displaced by the phosphate ions. With the largest P additions,  the adsorption is attributed to the nucleation, precipitation and recrystal-  lisation of aluminum phosphate (Imai et al., 1981).  Significantly, the adsorption capacity of allophane at higher phosphate  levels is directly related to the aluminum content of the sample (Theng et al.,  1982).  Regardless of the mechanism involved in the reaction the quantitative  description of soil--phosphate interactions is important for predicting phos-  phate fertilizer requirements of soils and critical levels in solution or as labile  phosphate in soils for optimum plant growth.  The Langmuir and Freundlich equations are often used to describe the  quantity/intensity relationships between solid and solution phase phosphates  in soils (Harter and Baker, 1977; Mead, 1981). The lack of agreement be-  tween phosphate adsorption data and these equations caused Syers et al.  (1973) to use a two-surface Langmuir equation.  The Freundlich equation has been criticized because it is an empirical  equation, with the constants having no physical meaning (Holford et al.,  1974). This equation has been rigorously derived by Sposito (1980). This  derivation requires only the applicability of the Langmuir equation to each  kind  of  adsorption sites regardless of the details of the adsorption  mechanism.  The Sokolowska isotherm is derived assuming that the Langmuir isotherm    121    is valid for individual (homotattic) sites and the energetic heterogeneity of  adsorption sites. The distribution of adsorption centers is supposed to be  continuous.  These three equations are based on the adsorption of ions on the solid  surfaces but none of them regard the possibility of secondary precipitation  phenomena.  Veith and Sposito (1977a, b) and Sposito (1982) have shown that the fit  of experimental sorption data to the Langmuir equation gives no informa-  tion concerning the chemical mechanism of the sorption reaction. Then it  follows that the parameters in the Langmuir equation, as deduced from a  statistical Langmuir plot of empirical data, will not have any particular  chemical meaning unless it has shown independently that only adsorption,  and not secondary precipitation, has occurred.  Also, any sorption reaction for which the distribution coefficient is a  finite and decreasing function of the amount sorbed and will extrapolate to  zero at a finite value of this sorbed amount can be represented mathematical-  ly by a two-surface Langmuir equation.  The purpose of this work was to determine the capacity of allophanic soil  samples to sorb inorganic P and to evaluate the applicability of the Langmuir,  Freundlich and Sokolowska equations in describing phosphate adsorption  isotherms. No attempt has been made to give any chemical interpretation to  the different equations.  In order to find a useful curve fitting isotherm equation for the data this  paper introduces a modification of the Langmuir two-surface equation pro-  posed by Syers et al. (1973). Different ways of plotting the Langmuir equa-  tion can produce different numerical values for the parameters.    MATERIALS AND METHODS    The sampled soil, an Andaquept (Andosol), has been described in detail  elsewhere (Ifiiguez and Barrag~n, 1974; Barrag~n and Ifiiguez, 1976), so only  the more pertinent information is given here. It is located at the north of  Navarra (Spain) at an altitude of 1,000 m, under beech forest and under a  humid climate (total precipitation 1,850 mm, annual average temperature  15.7). The predominant mineral is allophane, accompanied by vermiculite,  illite and biotite. The A horizon is 80 cm thick, very homogeneous in color  (10 YR 2/1 to N 2 moist color). Soil samples were obtained from this sur-  face horizon. The soil samples were air-dried in the laboratory and material  passing a 0.2 mm sieve was used for all analyses.  The physical and chemical properties are summarized in Table I.  Isotherms for the sorption of inorganic phosphate were obtained by shak-  ing 2 g of soil material with 20 ml of phosphate solution containing ap-  propriate amounts of NH4H2PO4 in 40 ml polypropylene tubes. The max-  imum addition was 0.5 mmol P/g of soil. The native adsorbed phosphate  evaluated by the Bray and Kurtz (1945) method was 30 ~g P/g of soil.    122    TABLE I  Some properties of soil samples    pH                  Organic C    Exchangeable cations (meq./100 g)        Ext. acidity  (%)                                                       (meq./100 g) H+    H20     KCl IN                    Ca      Mg      Na      K       A1  4.8     4.4         7.05         0.21    1.10    0.15    0.06    2.70    30    Bulk density     Surface area     SiO~ extracted (%)              AI203 extracted (%)  (1/3 bar)        (m2/g)    Segalen (I)    Dith-Citr (2)     Segalen (i)    Dith-Citr (2)  0.54             270              7.20           4.75             8.20           7.40    Fe:Oa extracted %    Segalen (1)    Dith-Citr (2)  2.90           3.30             30    Native adsorbed P (3)  (pg/g soil)    (1) Segalen (1968): 16 alternative extractions with OHNa and HCI.  (2) Aguilera and Jackson (1953) for Fe; Hashimoto and Jackson (1960) for Si and A1.  (3) Bray and Kurtz (1945).    After shaking for an hour the suspensions rested for 24 h, with occasional  shaking, in a bath at 25 -+ I. Then, the suspensions were centrifuged and  the supernatant solutions analyzed for P and the pH was measured. The  amount of sorbed phosphorus was calc