valm~s for part lI  permitted construction of the original experimental curve. This suggests that  the curve-splitting technique is satisfactory.  The uncorrected value for K:II should approach the addition of KI and  K:II obtained by the correction procedure. In fact good agreement was  obtained between these two values (0.622 mmol/g and 0.575 mmol/g,  respectively).  The Langmuir two-surface equation was far superior to tile one-surface  equation for fitting soil phosphate sorption data, which agrees with the  findings of Holford et al. (1974).  The Freundlich equation also closely predicted the actual phosphate  sorption better than the Langmuir one-surface equation. A linear trans-  formation of the data produced one straight line (Fig. 7).  The Sokolowska procedure permitted generation of the experimental  isotherm. It was necessary, however, to split the curve in two regions and to  calculate different parameters for low and high concentrations. The two  regions so obtained were different from those derived by the Langmuir  procedure.  Therefore, these observations suggest that the Langmuir two-surface, the  Freundlich and the Sokolowska equations would have been adequate to  describe the experimental process.  The same experimental data can be adjusted to the Freundlieh equation  with only one set of constants and to the Langmuir and Sokolowska equa-  tions with two different sets of parameters, one for the lower and the other  for the higher P concentration. In addition the two latter equations split the  isotherm in two regions that are different. These facts indicate that the  parameters have no chemical signification and that they are only "curve  fitting" parameters. Besides, different ways of plotting the Langmuir equa-  tion (Hofstee or conventional) can produce different numerical values for  the parameters, specially for the K1 constant.  Because of the large capacity for P sorption by the soil samples and the  irrelevant amount of native exchangeable P, it is possible that at low-equi-  librium P concentrations the sorption data fit well the Langmuir one-surface  equation. It is necessary to reach very-high-equilibrium P concentrations to  need the Langmuir two-surface equation to explain P sorption.  When the Langmuir two-surface, the Freundlich and the Sokolowska  equations are tested, the data fitted very well up to an equilibrium P con-  centration of 0.20 mmol/ml.  The high P concentrations used could make possible precipitation of P as  aluminum phosphate. The Langmuir equation can not be used to determine  whether adsorption or precipitation (formation of secondary minerals) is  occurring during anion fixation reactions in soils. The parameters in the  Langmuir equation can not be interpreted in terms of surface reactions  without additional independent evidence.    133    REFERENCES    Aguilera, N.H. and Jackson, M.L., 1953. Iron oxide removal from soils and clays. Soil Sci.  Soc. Am. J., 17: 359--364.  Barrag~in, E. and Ifiiguez, J., 1976. Weathering of clays minerals in a Navarre Andosol  (Spain). Clay Minerals, 11: 269--272.  Bray, R.H. and Kurtz, L.T., 1945. Determination of total organic and available forms of  phosphorus in soils. Soil Sci., 59: 39.  Charlot, G., 1966; Les m~thodes de la chimie analytique. Analyse quantitative min~rale.  Masson et Cie, Paris.  Gebhardt, H. and Coleman, N.T., 1974. Anion adsorption by allophanic tropical soils, III.  Phosphate adsorption. Soil Sci. Soc. Am. Proc., 38: 263--267.  Harter, R.D. and Baker, D.E., 1977. Applications and misapplications of the Langmuir  equation to soil adsorption phenomena. Soil Sci. Soc. Am. J., 41: 1077--1080.  Hashimoto, I. and Jackson, M.L., 1960. Rapid dissolution of allophane and kaolinite--  halloysite after deshydration. Proceedings of the 7th National Conference on Clays  and Clay Minerals. Pergamon Press, London.  Hayward, D.O. and Trapnell, B.M.W., 1964. Chemisorption. Butterworth and Co. Ltd.,  London, 2rid ed.  Hofstee, B.H